parsedComplaintsResult.impact: Sticky exhaust valves can cause the motorcycle to lose power, backfire, and stall, which can lead to accidents or leave the rider stranded.
symptoms: The motorcycle loses power
backfires
and stalls; the engine runs poorly; the exhaust valves stick open at any engine speed; the engine has a strong odor of exhaust; the motorcycle has a sudden loss of power on curves and straight roads.

parsedComplaintsResult.impact: Valve job issues can cause the motorcycle to backfire, stall, and lose power, which can lead to accidents or leave the rider stranded.
symptoms: The motorcycle backfires
stalls
and loses power; the valves stick; the engine runs poorly; the motorcycle has a strong odor of exhaust.

parsedComplaintsResult.impact: Carburetor jet settings issues can cause the motorcycle to lose power, backfire, and stall, which can lead to accidents or leave the rider stranded.
symptoms: The motorcycle loses power
backfires
and stalls; the engine runs poorly; the carburetor jet settings are too rich; excess gas is pulled into the combustion chamber
not being completely burnt
and carbon deposits are left on the valve seams of the rear cylinder head.

parsedComplaintsResult.impact: The failure of the fuel system can cause raw gasoline to leak onto the hot engine and exhaust pipes, creating a fire hazard and potentially leading to accidents or injuries.
symptoms: Gasoline leaking from the carburator
fuel overflow onto the hot engine and exhaust pipes
hissing sound
white smoke coming from the fuel hitting the hot motor and pushrod tubes.

parsedComplaintsResult.impact: The fuel leakage from the carburetor breather can cause a fire hazard, especially when the engine is hot, posing a significant risk to the rider and others nearby.
symptoms: Gasoline pours out of the breather when the engine is shut off and restarted
carburetor spills gas on the hot engine
repeated instances of fuel leakage during the day.

parsedComplaintsResult.impact: A faulty carburetor design or manufacturing can lead to fuel leakage, causing a fire hazard, and potentially resulting in accidents or injuries.
symptoms: Gasoline pours out of the breather when the engine is shut off and restarted
carburetor spills gas on the hot engine
repeated instances of fuel leakage during the day.
